00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:21.099
notion of the immortality of the soul which
means that, if you kill someone, you've just

00:53:21.099 --> 00:53:26.290
sent them off to a better world. Just a rite
of passage like a bar mitzvah or a midlife

00:53:26.290 --> 00:53:30.750
crisis. If you believe this is the only life
we have, I think that increases the value

00:53:30.750 --> 00:53:37.940
of life. Also the religions that hold out
the prospect of a future utopia, messianic

00:53:37.940 --> 00:53:44.660
age, a kingdom of heaven on earth, often write
into their chronology one last spasm of violence

00:53:44.660 --> 00:53:52.200
that brings about a perfect world and justifies
violence committed as a means to that end.

00:53:52.200 --> 00:53:59.749
Religions have also sanctified authority so
that the defiance of an ecclesiastical hierarchy

00:53:59.749 --> 00:54:07.279
is considered a heinous crime hence the burning
of heretics. It has licensed the maltreatment

00:54:07.279 --> 00:54:12.760
of animals, which in the Judeo-Christian tradition,
were put on earth for the benefit of humans.

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:17.430
It's licensed the beating of children since
they're possessed by the devil or subject

00:54:17.430 --> 00:54:22.310
to original sin and have to have the devil
literally beaten out of them to say nothing

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:29.559
of the treatment of homosexuality and other
punishment of violences of standards of purity

00:54:29.559 --> 00:54:36.030
-- sexual, dress, food, and so on. So, and
it's not surprising that religions have been

00:54:36.030 --> 00:54:41.789
responsible for some of the worst blood lettings
in history such as the Crusades, the European

00:54:41.789 --> 00:54:47.400
wars of religion, the Taiping Rebellion in
China was religiously motivated. This is not

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:53.480
to say religions are always bad. There have
been some periods in history when some religions

00:54:53.480 --> 00:55:00.210
have done good. There is the Quaker movement
which was both pacifist and abolitionist.

00:55:00.210 --> 00:55:04.569
Although they were a little late to the party
because 100 years before they were already

00:55:04.569 --> 00:55:10.970
briefs against slavery by John Locke and others.
And of course, the opponents of the abolitionist

00:55:10.970 --> 00:55:14.819
movements were themselves religious and there
were plenty of preachers who defended slavery.

00:55:14.819 --> 00:55:18.999
But at least that religion at that time in
history can be credited with having done some

00:55:18.999 --> 00:55:23.849
good. And there are some other examples as
well. So I would say that Christopher Hitchens

00:55:23.849 --> 00:55:31.489
went--, made an overstatement when he said
that religion poisons everything. That's going

00:55:31.489 --> 00:55:35.609
too far. But I think it has poisoned a lot
of things.

00:55:35.609 --> 00:55:42.430
&gt;&gt; Male #3: So your main metric for measuring
violence was deaths. The medical field has

00:55:42.430 --> 00:55:47.489
grown lot over the centuries. So what was
death in the 17th century was just injury

00:55:47.489 --> 00:55:52.180
now. Can you say something about the correlation
between the growth in medical field and the

00:55:52.180 --> 00:55:53.380
death and violence now.

00:55:53.380 --> 00:55:59.509
&gt;&gt; Steven: I think that the advance in medicine
has accounted for some small part of the decline

00:55:59.509 --> 00:56:04.539
in certain sectors like number of American
soldiers who have died in war. But I don't

00:56:04.539 --> 00:56:09.670
think it's been a major factor partly because,
until the 20th century, most doctors were

00:56:09.670 --> 00:56:17.950
quacks who killed as many people as they saved.
And also there were many forms of violence

00:56:17.950 --> 00:56:23.010
where there's just no -- medical treatment
was completely irrelevant. Capital punishment

00:56:23.010 --> 00:56:27.460
-- the whole point is you kill the person.
Doesn't matter how well the doctors are at

00:56:27.460 --> 00:56:33.900
saving someone who's been swinging from a
noose. Sieges in warfare. The doctors couldn't

00:56:33.900 --> 00:56:40.279
get in no matter what you did. Massive bombing
like Dresden and Hiroshima. Medical care may

00:56:40.279 --> 00:56:47.349
help at the margins but for someone who's
been vaporized, medical care is kind of beside

00:56:47.349 --> 00:56:54.289
the point. And other cases where whatever
life saving care may have been available,

00:56:54.289 --> 00:57:00.599
they were kept away. Indeed, I think the application
of life saving medical care, particularly

00:57:00.599 --> 00:57:05.380
in wartime, is itself a reflection of some
of these humanitarian currents. It used to

00:57:05.380 --> 00:57:13.230
be that soldiers were just expendable. They
were cannon fodder. Now at enormous expense,

00:57:13.230 --> 00:57:18.489
modern countries have tried to treat every
soldier's life as precious and the deployment

00:57:18.489 --> 00:57:23.910
of medical care is in part a reflection in
decrease in tolerance for violence.

00:57:23.910 --> 00:57:30.180
&gt;&gt; Male #4: So do you think like the negative
effects of technology advancement of technology.

00:57:30.180 --> 00:57:32.150
&gt;&gt; Steven: So can you lower the microphone.

00:57:32.150 --> 00:57:36.799
&gt;&gt; Male #4: So do you think the negative effects
of advancement of technology such as like

00:57:36.799 --> 00:57:41.849
nuclear weapons and better weapons and all
that have their instilled sort of fear to

00:57:41.849 --> 00:57:47.559
do wars and violence in general and sort of
in in some sense resolving the human dilemma.

00:57:47.559 --> 00:57:54.489
&gt;&gt; Steven: That's sometimes called the theory
of the nuclear peace and one scientist proposed

00:57:54.489 --> 00:58:01.550
the nuclear bomb be awarded the Nobel Peace
Prize. [laughter] I'm skeptical because of

00:58:01.550 --> 00:58:08.779
arguments by John Mueller suggested that the
trajectory of war would have unfolded in exactly

00:58:08.779 --> 00:58:13.320
the same way if nuclear weapons have never
been invented. Two reasons -- one of them

00:58:13.320 --> 00:58:18.989
is: World War II proved that conventional
warfare with good old fashioned tanks and

00:58:18.989 --> 00:58:26.079
artillery and aerial bombardment could do
so much damage that it served as a deterrent

00:58:26.079 --> 00:58:32.810
that was plenty scary enough to keep the superpowers
away from any thoughts of having a rematch

00:58:32.810 --> 00:58:39.260
any time soon. The other is that nuclear weapons
are so disproportionately destructive compared

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:46.460
to any strategic war aim other than in the
"Strange-Lovian" all out annihilation that

00:58:46.460 --> 00:58:52.489
they've almost been irrelevant in the actual
conduct of wars and associated deterrents.

00:58:52.489 --> 00:59:00.299
They've fallen into a taboo category and are
just not considered an option, a live option

00:59:00.299 --> 00:59:07.170
on the menu of war fighting strategies. Countries
know that which is why, very often, a non-nuclear

00:59:07.170 --> 00:59:12.660
power has defied a nuclear one. Just what
the situation you expect nuclear deterrents

00:59:12.660 --> 00:59:19.239
to be most effective. When Argentina tried
to conquer the Falkland islands, they knew

00:59:19.239 --> 00:59:25.269
that Britain would not retaliate by turning
Buenos Aires into a radioactive crater. The

00:59:25.269 --> 00:59:30.030
nuclear effect had become, by all intents
and purposes, a bluff. And so, that's why

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:33.369
I think two reasons why I don't think it's
been the major factor.

00:59:33.369 --> 00:59:40.759
&gt;&gt; Male #5: One quick question which is why
or what do you see in the projection of total

00:59:40.759 --> 00:59:46.769
peace keeping force head count given that
that was one of the stabilizing influences

00:59:46.769 --> 00:59:53.980
and seemed to be on a rather painful trajectory.
Have you extrapolated where that takes us.

00:59:53.980 --> 00:59:56.720
&gt;&gt; Steven: The number of peace keeping forces
on a painful trajectory.

00:59:56.720 --> 01:00:02.130
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Well, in the sense that the growth
is very large at least over the last couple

01:00:02.130 --> 01:00:08.759
of decades and it wasn't clear whether it
was asymptoting or needed to be a continuous

01:00:08.759 --> 01:00:11.459
increase in tax to maintain stability.

01:00:11.459 --> 01:00:17.309
&gt;&gt; Steven: Oh, I see. I consider it highly
benevolent development given the studies that

01:00:17.309 --> 01:00:23.690
show peace keeping works. And here I'm borrowing
