01:00:23.690 --> 01:00:29.480
the War on War where he argues that it's the
-- that exponential increase in number of

01:00:29.480 --> 01:00:37.289
blue helmeted soldiers, where they're actually
seriously armed and prepared to use the arms,

01:00:37.289 --> 01:00:44.190
that drives down the total rate of death in
war. Kind of an international Leviathan. The

01:00:44.190 --> 01:00:51.349
limiting step there is the reluctance of third
parties to put their own citizens at risk

01:00:51.349 --> 01:00:54.990
to prevent wars involving other countries.
It's kind of an act of altruism.

01:00:54.990 --> 01:01:00.079
&gt;&gt; Male #5: And then the second question is
the previous one of the previous questions

01:01:00.079 --> 01:01:06.710
was around medical science and the degree
to which it reduced death as opposed to perhaps

01:01:06.710 --> 01:01:15.480
a more a metric of the damage to society not
just individuals but if you twisted that around

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:22.789
a little bit and you said that the survival
rate from more moderate wounds has increased

01:01:22.789 --> 01:01:26.999
dramatically compared to say the civil war
where getting a splinter could kill you in

01:01:26.999 --> 01:01:36.020
the wrong environment. These people coming
back now diffuse an awareness of war that

01:01:36.020 --> 01:01:41.589
previously wasn't available because it was
a critical discontinuous step function. The

01:01:41.589 --> 01:01:46.730
person either came back or never came back
but they never came back injured. Is there

01:01:46.730 --> 01:01:52.370
any correlation that you could consider there
&gt;&gt;Steven: Would that be a pacifying force

01:01:52.370 --> 01:01:54.869
as people are reminded of the human costs
of war.

01:01:54.869 --> 01:01:59.869
&gt;&gt; Male #5: Well, and it's a really visual
force when you see people with amputations.

01:01:59.869 --> 01:02:04.420
&gt;&gt; Steven: It's conceivable. I think there
are a number of technologies that make the

01:02:04.420 --> 01:02:09.280
human cost of war more visible to more people
even if you don't know someone you might have

01:02:09.280 --> 01:02:13.390
seen their story on television for example
which would not have been true in the past.

01:02:13.390 --> 01:02:19.819
So war I think is less often an abstraction
something that's just glorious and thrilling

01:02:19.819 --> 01:02:25.460
and spiritual and holy which was the attitude
towards war the end of the 19th century. The

01:02:25.460 --> 01:02:31.151
realities of the first world war conveyed
by literature, first hand accounts, and so

01:02:31.151 --> 01:02:34.619
on did start to scare people straight.

01:02:34.619 --> 01:02:39.660
&gt;&gt; Male #6: So concurrently with the decline
in violence over the last century there's

01:02:39.660 --> 01:02:45.859
been also an increase kind of alarming in
the number of people in the United States

01:02:45.859 --> 01:02:51.180
incarcerated. Is there any concern that some
of this decline in violence is coming at a

01:02:51.180 --> 01:02:58.609
cost of decline in freedom. Sort of like a
strange impasse we come to where what to do

01:02:58.609 --> 01:03:01.709
with this space left by violent uprisings.

01:03:01.709 --> 01:03:10.979
&gt;&gt; Steven: I think that is a valid concern.
The American incarceration binge has probably

01:03:10.979 --> 01:03:17.019
been one of the factors that has led the rate
of violent crime to plummet since 1992. It

01:03:17.019 --> 01:03:22.900
